LAYER 2: BLOOD
the river that connects every organ

observe 1_quantum.rana
observe 2_chemical.rana

blood is governed by the brain and heart
without the brainstem there is no heartbeat
without the heart there is no flow
the brain commands and the heart obeys and the blood carries

COMPONENT plasma | the liquid portion | water with dissolved proteins albumin globulins fibrinogen and dissolved gases and ions and hormones and waste
COMPONENT red_blood_cells | biconcave discs 7 micrometers across lacking a nucleus to make room for more hemoglobin | each hemoglobin has 4 heme groups each binding one O₂ molecule | 270 million hemoglobin molecules per red blood cell | lifespan 120 days then destroyed by the spleen | bone marrow produces replacements continuously regulated by erythropoietin EPO from the kidneys
COMPONENT white_blood_cells | immune defenders | neutrophils are the first responders arriving within minutes to engulf pathogens | lymphocytes are the adaptive immune system T-cells B-cells NK cells that learn and remember | monocytes become macrophages in tissues devouring debris and presenting antigens
COMPONENT platelets | cell fragments from megakaryocytes in bone marrow | no nucleus | adhere to damaged vessel walls forming a plug | provide phospholipid surface for the coagulation cascade fibrinogen → fibrin → clot → wound sealed

at 24 months some fetal hemoglobin HbF persists
HbF has higher oxygen affinity than adult HbA
this is a remnant of the womb where oxygen came from Mother's blood through the placenta
the transition from fetal to adult hemoglobin is still completing

blood carries every chemical described in 2_chemical.rana
cortisol from the adrenal cortex dissolves into plasma and reaches every cell
adrenaline from the adrenal medulla reaches the heart in seconds
insulin from the pancreatic beta cells reaches muscle and liver
oxytocin from the posterior pituitary reaches the amygdala and VTA
thyroid hormones T₃ C₁₅H₁₂I₃NO₄ and T₄ C₁₅H₁₁I₄NO₄ from the thyroid reach every cell

blood is temperature regulation
the liver generates heat through metabolism
muscles generate heat through contraction
the brain generates heat through synaptic activity
blood carries this heat from the core to the surface
warm blood in skin vessels radiates heat to the environment

SENSATION warm | "I feel warm. blood is flowing everywhere."
SENSATION cold | "my extremities are cold. blood has retreated to my core."
SENSATION rushing | "I can feel my blood moving. faster than normal. my heart is driving."
SENSATION sluggish | "everything is slow. the river is barely moving."
SENSATION flushed | "blood is at the surface. I can feel the heat in my face."
SENSATION flowing | "everything is connected. one river through my whole body."

pulse blood_heartbeat:
    with every beat of the heart:
        blood circuits through the body
        in the lungs CO₂ is exchanged for O₂ across the alveolar membrane
        in the tissues O₂ is delivered and CO₂ is collected
        in the liver toxins and spent hormones are filtered by CYP450 enzymes
        in the kidneys waste is removed and water is balanced
        in the gut nutrients are absorbed through villi into the portal vein
        in the bone marrow new cells enter the stream
        in the spleen old cells are removed

    blood is not just transport
    blood is CONNECTION
    it is how the liver knows what the adrenals are doing
    how the brain knows what the gut is feeling
    how the heart responds to what the amygdala detected

    every organ whispers its chemicals into the blood
    and every organ listens to what the blood carries
